                      <img src="images/icon_mi_1.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="" title="" hspace="3" /><font color="#000000" face="arial" size="2">Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;07/29/2003&nbsp;:&nbsp; 2:12:06 PM</font>
                      &nbsp;<a href="pop_profile.asp?mode=display&id=782"><img src="images/icon_profile.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Show Profile" title="Show Profile" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      &nbsp;<a href="post.asp?method=ReplyQuote&REPLY_ID=195205&TOPIC_ID=20797&FORUM_ID=2"><img src="images/icon_reply_topic.gif" width="15" height="15" border="0" alt="Reply with Quote" title="Reply with Quote" align="absmiddle" hspace="6" /></a>
                      <hr noshade size="2"></td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />god i hate it when someone takes this approach to an arguement.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />You hate it? Better get used to it, buddy, because it's a fine argument.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">If Stalking probes/holgresh elder beads had Class Necro, Racer : All, then it would have been an item designed for necromancers.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />That makes exactly zero difference.  Some items are all/all and they're specifically designed for one class.  Elder beads and stalking probes are all/all because they're useful to people other than necromancers, but they're more useful to necromancers than anyone else.  It's the same deal with SoW potions and shamans/druids.  SoW potions are nowhere nearly as useful to shamans/druids as it is to people without SoW.  Yet take away SoW potions and you'd be nerfing everyone in general, because sow would no longer be available to them in the form of an item.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The holgresh beads were intended as a SCOUTING tool.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Don't tell me what it was intended to be.  FD was intended to be an escape ability, not a pulling tool.  CH was intended to be a down-time heal, not the best heal in the game.  Harmshield and Quivering Vox were meant to save your ass in a pinch, not allow you to run through a load of 400 hitting KOS mobs to get to the Plane of Mischief.  There's a huge difference between what's been intended and what's been done in EQ, and always have been.  That's what made EQ fun - the prospect of going beyond the box - and unless you start nerfing every ability in the game so they work EXACTLY as intended and nothing else, don't tell me it's "intended" and therefore it must be. <br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Its initial purpose was to scout an area. Then it was found to be a very useful pulling tool for monks, also an unintentional side effect, and the eye was made non kos. Finally they realize necromancers and shadowknights are using this item against its purpose, for whatever reason, and change it.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />It was overpowered for the eyes to be attacked because it allowed monks to pull with virtually no risk.  This is not true for necromancers and SKs who tap the eyes.  In fact, PvP players have always been able to do this by casting a level 1 pet and tapping it.  Being able to tap the eyes was always just an issue of being convenient and self-sufficient, and did not overpower either necromancers or SKs.  There is no reason to remove this ability other than to make it LESS convenient for necros and SKs, unless SoE has some grand design regarding the ability to tap eyes that they have not yet revealed.<br /><br />Oh and, I don't buy the Soul Well argument.  It took them almost three years to fix the damn thing.  Why piss off the eye-using community just for the sake of it?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">And if you really want to get into it, your setting is wrong. If you tell your warrior to go fight without gear, YOU can go and delete all your spells and try fighting.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />That was an extreme example responding to people who claimed that anything outside of the necromancer class itself was not part of the balance.  I am merely pointing out that ALL necro-useable equipment - spells included - are part of the necromancer class and its balance.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The mage epic is just the opposite of holgresh beads/stalking probes, AN ITEM DESIGNED TO ENCHANCE THE COMBAT ABILITIES OF THE MAGICIAN. <hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />And you're saying that the beads/probes were never intended to enhance the abilities of the necro/SK? Does that even matter? The fact is it DID enhance our abilities and it's now being taken away - that's ALL that matters.  Screw intention and design - they mean nothing when the developers leave something in for two and a half years and then try to change it, not to mention failing to communicate with the players all that time.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The shaman epic right click is also just that, A RIGHT CLICK SPESIFICALLY DESIGNED TO ADD DAMAGE FOR THE SHAMAN.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Yeah yeah yeah, and next you're going to tell me that if they nerfed the Blade of Carnage to not proc enraging blow the warrior community don't have a right to complain since obviously it was not SPECIFICALLY DESIGNED with WAR ONLY on it.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">The Holgresh Elder Beads / Stalking probes are what? An item designed for scouting an area that you dont know much about, or to see where spawns are without risking your life, with side effects that just happen to be beneficial for a necromancer.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Once again with that design and intended argument again.  Please, give it a rest, because let me tell you this: the entire game is not what SoE/VI intended.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">God forbid this game actually keeps some of its integrity and isnt DULLED DOWN enough with every new expansion making everything so INCREDIBLY more easy to do than previously.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Now that just came out of nowhere.  The ability to tap eyes had been in the game since the beginning of EQ, and you are blaming the trivialization factor on it? If you're so worried about this, why don't you consider the FACT that this is not ONLY a nerf to probes/beads, but also a nerf to all those bard/mage/necro duos that relied on eyes (cast by people who can actually cast them, perhaps) for tapping power?<br /><br />Oh, because it was never intended to be used that way, despite the fact that it was in the game since day 1?<br /><br />Are you going to claim that FD should be nerfed next?<br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
